I also extended JUnit to count the assertions and had to modify the
Assert.java file.  I then wrote the test in the TestAssert.java file and
it worked fine.  Maybe you&#39;re testing where it&#39;s harder to do.

&gt; (inside TestCaseTest)
&gt; public void testAssertionCount() {
&gt;         TestCase assertionCount = new TestCase(&quot;assertionCount&quot;) {
&gt;                 protected void runTest() {
&gt;                 }
&gt;                 public void testAssertionCount(){
&gt;                         assertTrue(true);
&gt;                         assertTrue(&quot;&quot;,true);
&gt;                         assertEquals(true,true);
&gt;                         assertEquals(&quot;&quot;,true,true);
&gt;                 }
&gt;         };
&gt;         verifyAssertionCount(assertionCount);
&gt; }

I would code something like that:

public void testAssertionCount () {
   setAssertCount(0);  // reset the assertions&#39; counter
   assertTrue(true);
   assertTrue(&quot;&quot;,true);
   assertEquals(true,true);
   assertEquals(&quot;&quot;,true,true);
   assertTrue(&quot;Wrong assertion #&quot;, 4 == assertCount());
}

I assume that the setAssertCount and assertCount methods are accessible
within a TestCase (which makes sense).  In my case they are defined in
the Assert class.

